		<title type="html"><![CDATA[IDRC&#8217;s participation in the Google Summer of Code 2010, a success!]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca/archives/712" />
		<id>http://scyp.idrc.ocad.ca/?p=712</id>
		<updated>2010-10-28T21:31:05Z</updated>
		<published>2010-10-28T21:18:25Z</published>
		<category scheme="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca" term="Events" /><category scheme="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca" term="code" /><category scheme="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca" term="Google" /><category scheme="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca" term="IDRC" /><category scheme="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca" term="mobile" /><category scheme="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca" term="Tekla" />		<summary type="html"><![CDATA[The Inclusive Design Research Centre has completed a very fruitful participation in the Google Summer of Code 2010. We supervised five students who worked on five different open source projects; three of which were relevant to the mobile space. These three mobile projects were: an ATutor mobile theme, by Alison Benjamin, a native iPhone application [&#8230;]]]></summary>
		<content type="html" xml:base="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca/archives/712"><![CDATA[<p>The Inclusive Design Research Centre has completed a very fruitful participation in the <a href="http://code.google.com/soc/">Google Summer of Code</a> 2010. We supervised five students who worked on five different open source projects; three of which were relevant to the mobile space. These three mobile projects were:</p>
<ul>
<li>an ATutor mobile theme, by Alison Benjamin,</li>
<li>a native iPhone application for ATutor Social with VoiceOver support and push notification, by Anh Quang Do, and </li>
<li><a href="http://scyp.idrc.ocad.ca/projects/tekla">Tekla</a>, an app that allows powered wheelchair users to control Android handsets, by <a href="http://www.metronews.ca/toronto/local/article/610970--paralyzed-man-s-work-helps-disabled-kids--page1">Eric Wan</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>All these projects were received with interest during the Google Summer of Code Mentor Summit at Googleplex this past weekend and, although many developers are unfamiliar with the best practices in accessibility, all of them understood right away the value of inclusive design in all contexts, particularly in the mobile space. <a href="http://idrc.ocad.ca/index.php?option=com_content&#038;task=view&#038;id=387&#038;Itemid=116">Jorge Silva</a>, researcher from the IDRC, chaired two sessions at the summit, one on the Tekla project: <a href="http://typewith.me/TouchFreeMobile">&#8220;&#8216;touch-free&#8217; access to mobile devices&#8221;</a>, and another one on <a href="http://typewith.me/indoorpositioning">open source indoor positioning</a>. Googlers were so excited about our work on Tekla that they offered to feature it in <a href="http://google-opensource.blogspot.com/">Google&#8217;s own open source blog</a> as well as the <a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/">Sparkfun</a> hacker store, were we got the parts for the Tekla shield, a device that enables a Bluetooth link between powered wheelchairs and mobile phones.</p>
]]></content>
