		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Tekla case CAD drawing available]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca/archives/638" />
		<id>http://scyp.idrc.ocad.ca/?p=638</id>
		<updated>2010-09-07T15:47:08Z</updated>
		<published>2010-09-07T15:38:06Z</published>
		<category scheme="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca" term="Uncategorized" />		<summary type="html"><![CDATA[We have done quite a bit of work during the summer getting the Tekla on-screen keyboard ready for Android. Amongst other features, Tekla will enable powered wheelchair users to access their smartphones directly from their wheelchairs via bluetooth. This will require a small, custom piece of hardware mounted on the wheelchair (called the Tekla shield), [&#8230;]]]></summary>
		<content type="html" xml:base="https://mobile-accessibility.idrc.ocadu.ca/archives/638"><![CDATA[<div style="width: 290px" class="wp-caption alignright"><object width="280" height="235"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/wdw8NN8Yek8?fs=1&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/wdw8NN8Yek8?fs=1&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="280" height="235"></embed></object><p class="wp-caption-text">Prototype tekla case</p></div>
<p>We have done quite a bit of work during the summer getting the <a href="http://scyp.idrc.ocad.ca/projects/tekla">Tekla</a> on-screen keyboard ready for Android. Amongst other features, <a href="http://scyp.idrc.ocad.ca/projects/tekla">Tekla</a> will enable powered wheelchair users to access their smartphones directly from their wheelchairs via bluetooth. This will require a small, custom piece of hardware mounted on the wheelchair (called the Tekla shield), and since this hardware will be exposed to the weather, it needs a protective case.</p>
<p>This is what Zongyi Yang, an Enginerring student at the University of Toronto, has been working on for the past few days. Check out the video of the prototype case, we will be using a 3D printer soon to create a sample that we can mount on <a href="http://www.metronews.ca/toronto/local/article/610970--paralyzed-man-s-work-helps-disabled-kids--page1">Eric Wan</a>&#8216;s chair. While Zongyi has been working on the hardware, Eric has been making significant contributions to the software since he will be using <a href="http://scyp.idrc.ocad.ca/projects/tekla">Tekla</a> to take notes at school now that he will be starting a Master&#8217;s in Engineering at the University of Toronto.</p>
]]></content>
